  "prompt": "Is buying cannon 1200D a good idea for beginner in 2016 or should I go for 1300D?",
  "response": "As of 2016, both the Canon 1200D (also known as the Rebel T5 in some markets) and the Canon 1300D (Rebel T6) are entry-level DSLRs aimed at beginners. Here are some points to consider when deciding between the two:\n\n### Canon 1200D:\n- **Sensor**: 18 MP APS-C sensor.\n- **LCD Screen**: 3-inch fixed LCD, with 460,000 dots.\n- **ISO Range**: 100-6400 (expandable to 12800).\n- **Video**: 1080p video recording.\n- **Connectivity**: No Wi-Fi or NFC.\n\n### Canon 1300D:\n- **Sensor**: 18 MP APS-C sensor (same as 1200D, but slight improvements in processing).\n- **LCD Screen**: 3-inch fixed LCD, with 920,000 dots (better resolution than 1200D).\n- **ISO Range**: 100-6400 (expandable to 12800).\n- **Video**: 1080p video recording.\n- **Connectivity**: Wi-Fi and NFC for easy sharing and remote control.\n\n### Considerations:\n1. **Price**: The 1200D might be cheaper, but the price difference could be minimal depending on where you buy.\n2. **Features**: The 1300D offers better connectivity features (Wi-Fi and NFC) and a higher resolution LCD, which can enhance usability.\n3. **Image Quality**: Both cameras have similar image quality since they share the same sensor, but the 1300D's processing may lead to slightly improved performance in certain situations.\n4. **Future Proofing**: If you\u2019re planning to use the camera for a longer time, the added features of the 1300D may make it a more viable option.\n\n### Recommendation:\nIf the price difference is not significant and you can find the 1300D, it would be a better investment due to its improved features. However, if you're on a tight budget, the 1200D is still a solid camera for a beginner. Ultimately, choose the one that fits your budget and needs best!",
